  "body": "Here's a random hello react fiddle I plucked from google\n\n```\nvar Hello = React.createClass({\n  render: function() {\n    return <div>Hello {this.props.name}</div>;\n  }\n});\n\nReactDOM.render(\n  <Hello name=\"World\" />,\n  document.getElementById('container')\n);\n```\n\nReference: https://jsfiddle.net/reactjs/69z2wepo/\n\nNow suppose for formatting/stylistic purposes, I want to format that inline return expression for like so:\n\n```\nvar Hello = React.createClass({\n  render: function() {\n    return \n        (<div>\n            <p>Hello {this.props.name}</p>\n         </div>);\n  }\n});\n\nReactDOM.render(\n  <Hello name=\"World\" />,\n  document.getElementById('container')\n);\n```\n\nReact now throws an invariant violation on `Hello.render(): A valid ReactComponent must be returned. You may have returned undefined, an array or some other invalid object` all because I put the actual expression in a new line instead of the same line as the return statement.\n\nReference: https://jsfiddle.net/gdgoqva7/1/\n\nCan react be made more lenient so that the 2nd example is allowed?\n\nThe react version referenced in both fiddles is v0.14.6\n",
